args: You never ask to come along when I go\nfind new merchandise, Cleo. What gives?
I'm hoping to get my hands on some\ningredients I usually struggle to find.

Hmm. Well, I definitely know of places
where you can find rare and unique
delicacies, but that still doesn't explain
why you're suddenly into this now.
I want to expand my cooking horizons.\nWho knows what sort of ingredients I\nmight encounter out on assignment?
Well, like I said, I think I know\njust the place to take you!
Heavens, look at all these mushrooms\nand medicinal herbs!
Amazing, right? I learned about the place\nfrom a trader friend of mine.
And you're letting me in on the secret?!
Of course! I have a good relationship\nwith 'em, so I'm free to use this place\nhowever I see fit.
Be that for my own supplies,\nor as a bargaining chip.
Look, you and me are good pals and all,\nbut I'm still gonna need a little something\nin return for showing you this place.
Think maybe you could help me pick out\nsome medicinal herbs for my wares?\nYou've got a knack for that sorta thing.
Heh. That sounds like a fair trade to me.
Right then! Where should we begin?
Hey, howzabout a break before we head\ninto town so I can sell this stuff?
Of course. Also, thank you again for today,\nif I haven't been clear on that front.
You helped me get my hands on some\ntruly unique ingredients!
And YOUR help picking out those\nmedicinal herbs was invaluable!
You're so quick and precise! If it were me,\nI'd have been standing there scratching\nmy head till the sun went down.
Which reminds me, I need to note\nthis new inventory in my ledger.
Er, this is going to take a bit, Cleo.\nYou mind waiting a little longer?
Is there anything I can do to help?
Seriously? Well, I suppose you could cut\nthe stems off these mushrooms.
Can you not sell them as they are?
Yeah, the stems are pretty tough eating,\nso they tend to sell better without 'em.
Oh, and could you split these blue plums\nin two and take out the pits?
They'll sell better if they're pitted\nand preserved in sugar.
This all feels rather like a waste of food.
Customers want things that are ready to\neat and easy to cook; it saves them time.
(Is there anything I can do?\nOh, of course!)
Francesca, would it be all right for me\nto take the leftover bits once we're done\nwith the prepwork?
Sure, knock yourself out.\nEr, but mind if I ask why?
I'm going to make us lunch!
People don't like these mushroom stems\nbecause they are dry and flavorless, yes?
But that's no reason they wouldn't taste\nwonderful in a spicy soup!
Yeah, I suppose dryness doesn't matter\nin a soupâ€”and if it's spicy enough,\nthe flavor won't, either.
And at the same time, they will provide\nmuch-needed texture.
Pretty smart there, Cleo.\nSo what about the plum pits?
They're too hard and bitter to eat as-is,\nbut they have a lovely fragrance.
I plan to break them up into chips\nand roast them on an open fire.
Indeed. And now I will use it to smoke\nthis leaf-wrapped fish.
*munch* Okay, THAT is legit good.\nIt doesn't taste fishy at all!
Wonderful! I roasted some herbs that\ncounteract fishiness along with the\nplum pits, so I'm happy it worked.
You know, I bet I could use this to keep\nfish fresh over long distances!
I can't believe you managed to turn a\nbunch of stuff I was gonna toss out into\nmarketable goods. This is a major score!
Being quick is all well and good,\nbut not wasting food is also a key part\nof being a great chef.
The more food there is to eat,\nthe fewer people go hungry.
As a purveyor of fine foods, I wanna take\nthose words and tattoo them on my face!\n...I mean, not literally. But you know.
Say, have you ever thought of collecting \nyour recipes in a book?
Yeah, a book! Your food-saving ways would\nbe invaluable for households that are\nstruggling to make ends meet.
It would be an instant best seller,\nand I'd be happy to give you the\nlion's share of the profits.
Heck, we could make a special edition\nsigned by you for some added value.\nOr maybe even hold a signing!
